XLVI. ¹ Perdundae reipublicae] Cortius is of opinion these words are in the genitive rather than the dative, and that the construction is the same as that of conservandae libertatis atque auyendae reipublicae, cap. vt-M.

Perdundae reipublicae.] Add to Mair's note, Perizon. on Sanct. Miner-v. 4, 4, p. 554, makes these words the dat., govemed by idone- am, understood. I agree with him. An excellent commentator on Liv. says, ‘⁶ Esse alicujus rei faciendae, pro pertinere ad rem illam faci· endam elegans est locutio. Liv. 3, e. 24, Frustrationem eam Ieyis tollendae esse. Sic libro eodem c. 31, quaeque aequandae libertatis essent, &c.‚ et lib. eod. c. 39, quod unum exaequandae sit libertatis.'' In ch. 6, conservandae libertatis show that augendae reip. are in the gen.; but oneri here proves reipub. perdendae to be the dat.-—C.

² Caeparium quemdam] Muret. on Cic. 3, orat. against Cat„ reads Caeparium quendam, but not Q„ for Cic. nameshim M. Coeparius. The reading in the text should be, Itemque Coeparium quemdam, as Krit- zius has it, without, however, noticing Muretus—C.

³ Terracinensem] Terracina was a town in Latium, anciently called Anxur, and hence the patrial Terracinensis.-M.
